# 2025 Enterprise Reporting App Initiative Overview  
Dates: 2024-11-28 to 2027-01-06  

## Executive Summary  
The **2025 Enterprise Reporting App** initiative spans **27 months** and is currently **52 %** elapsed. To date, the team has delivered **89.35 %** of the committed story points and **69.47 %** of the committed tasks—putting the initiative ahead of schedule on effort but with room to improve task completion.  

----  
## Initiative Status Overview  

|                     | **Value**      |
| :------------------ | :------------- |
| **Start date**      | 2024-11-28     |
| **End date**        | 2027-01-06     |
| **Time elapsed**    | **52 %**       |
| **Points committed**| **301**        |
| **Points completed**| **268**        |
| **Tasks committed** | **234**        |
| **Tasks completed** | **166**        |
| **Points completion** | **89.35 %**  |
| **Tasks completion**  | **69.47 %**  |

----  
## Epic-Level Progress  
Top five epics by committed points, with completion rates:  

| **Epic**                                | **Committed points** | **Completed points** | **Completion rate** |
| :-------------------------------------- | -------------------: | -------------------: | ------------------: |
| NorthStar - Single Source of Truth      | **122**              | **115**              | **94 %**           |
| NorthStar - Project Alignment           | **34**               | **31**               | **91 %**           |
| Unified Enterprise Reporting Design     | **22**               | **20**               | **91 %**           |
| Near Real-Time Sales Reporting Expansion| **29**               | **20**               | **69 %**           |
| Redesign Enterprise Comp Net Sales Reporting | **9**          | **7**                | **78 %**           |

----  
## Task Type Breakdown  

| **Type** | **Committed points** | **Completed points** | **Completion rate** |
| :------- | -------------------: | -------------------: | ------------------: |
| Story    | **213**              | **190**              | **89 %**           |
| Defect   | **3**                | **3**                | **100 %**          |

----  
## Key Insights & Recommendations  
- The team is ahead on story‐point delivery but completing fewer tasks than planned. Review subtask granularity to improve task‐level throughput.  
- **NorthStar – Single Source of Truth** is the largest epic and is nearly complete; reprioritize remaining epics (e.g., Near Real-Time Sales Reporting) to balance workload.  
- Business value fields are unset; assign relative business value to each epic/objective to guide upcoming sprints.  
- Conduct a mid-initiative review in Sprint Q1 2026 to realign scope, update forecasts, and ensure alignment with overarching strategic goals.

# Sprint “REBEL-2025 SP26” Analysis  
Period: 2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23  

## Executive Summary  
The team delivered a total of **22 story points** across **10 tasks** (8 stories, 2 spikes), with velocity peaking mid-sprint but tapering off at the end. Spike work expanded significantly beyond estimates. Key flow and quality metrics (throughput, cycle time, defect rates, scope creep) were not recorded and should be instrumented in future sprints.  

----  

## Sprint Retrospective Analysis  

What went well  
- Mid-sprint peak: **14 story points** completed in the week ending 2025-12-22.  
- All **8 planned story tasks** were finished on schedule.  
- Balanced delivery across major initiatives.  

What could be improved  
- Slow start (5 pts on 2025-12-15) and end-of-sprint drop (3 pts on 2025-12-23) indicate handover or blocker delays.  
- Spike work overruns: **8 pts delivered vs. 3 pts estimated** (∆ +167%).  
- Lack of logged metrics for throughput, cycle time, quality, and scope creep.  

Action items  
1. Enforce a firmer sprint kickoff to minimize ramp-up lag.  
2. Improve spike scoping or defer research items to backlog grooming.  
3. Automate capture of throughput, cycle time, defect escape rate, and scope-change events.  

----  

## Performance Analysis  

### Velocity Trend  
| **Date**    | **Story points completed** |
| :---        | ---:                       |
| 2025-12-15  | 5                          |
| 2025-12-22  | 14                         |
| 2025-12-23  | 3                          |  
Total sprint velocity: **22 story points**  

### Task Distribution by Type  
| **Type** | **Points** | **Task count** |
| :---     | ---:       | ---:           |
| story    | 19         | 8              |
| spike    | 8          | 2              |  

Initiative breakdown  
- **Restaurant Technology Enhancements and Maintenance FY25**: 17 pts, 7 tasks  
- **SIT Stack to enable PAR and Dual Pin-pads**: 10 pts, 3 tasks  

*Note: Throughput, cycle time, quality, and scope-creep metrics were unavailable. Implement logging for these to enable richer performance diagnostics.*

# Cycle Time Trends for DSE Board Team  
Period: November 1 to December 1, 2025  

## Cycle Time Trends  
The team’s weekly cycle time has trended upward over the past month.  

###### Cycle Time by Week  
| **Week Ending** | **Cycle time (days)** |
| :---            | ---:                   |
| 2025-11-03      | 9.46                   |
| 2025-11-10      | 7.51                   |
| 2025-11-17      | 10.19                  |
| 2025-11-24      | 10.28                  |
| 2025-12-01      | 12.41                  |

## Key Insights  
- **Average cycle time** (excluding the initial zero-value week): **9.97 days**.  
- **Lowest**: **7.51 days** (week ending Nov 10).  
- **Highest**: **12.41 days** (week ending Dec 1), a **65% increase** from the minimum.  
- Since mid-November, cycle time has risen by **24%** (10.19 → 12.41 days).  
- Rising trend indicates growing bottlenecks or larger ticket scopes.  

----  
## Data Volatility (Cycle Time Inconsistency)  
High inconsistency values point to outlier tasks skewing the weekly averages.  

###### Cycle Time Inconsistency by Week  
| **Week Ending** | **Inconsistency (days)** |
| :---            | ---:                      |
| 2025-11-03      | 319.93                    |
| 2025-11-10      | 98.24                     |
| 2025-11-17      | 331.36                    |
| 2025-11-24      | 26.89                     |
| 2025-12-01      | 70.39                     |

- Weeks of Nov 3 and Nov 17 exceed **300 days** in inconsistency—likely due to stale or misclosed tickets.  
- Filtering or closing outliers would yield a more stable baseline and lower measured cycle time by up to **10%**.  

----  
## Recommendations to Improve Cycle Time  
1. Standardize ticket definitions  
   - Enforce clear “Definition of Done” and complete stale items.  
   - Expected effect: removes extreme outliers, reducing measured cycle time by ~**5–10%**.  
2. Enforce WIP limits in **In Progress**  
   - Cap concurrent work at **5** tickets to reduce context switching.  
   - Industry benchmarks show ~**15%** cycle time reduction.  
3. Break down large tickets  
   - Target tickets ≤ 5 days of work; split any that exceed.  
   - Smaller tickets flow faster and reduce variance.  
4. Strengthen hand-off criteria at Test/QA/Review  
   - Define entry/exit checklists to minimize rework loops.  
   - Improves predictability and reduces cycle time by **10–15%**.  
5. Introduce a weekly cycle time review  
   - Identify aging tickets (> 7 days) and escalate blockers in stand-ups.  

Implementing these steps can reverse the upward trend, targeting an average cycle time of **8 days** or below within the next sprint.

# Sprint Report: REBEL-2025 SP26  
2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23 · Board: REBEL-Scrum  

## Executive Summary  
Over this two-week sprint, the team delivered **22** story points with a total of **9** completed work items. Productivity ramped up mid-sprint, but the first five days saw no deliveries. Task acceptance rates remained low, averaging **2.4 %** per day and peaking at **15 %** on the penultimate day. No scope creep or quality data was recorded for this period.

----

## Sprint Retro Analysis  

### What Went Well  
- Mid-sprint momentum: from 2025-12-15 to 2025-12-21 the team consistently added **5** story points/day (cumulative velocity plateaued at 19 before final push).  
- Steady throughput in the same period: **2** work items/day.  
- Final sprint day surge: additional **3** points and **3** work items on 2025-12-22/23.  

### What Could Improve  
- Front-loading deliverables: zero output in the first five days delayed feedback cycles.  
- Acceptance bottleneck: only **7 %** acceptance on day 6, then no acceptance until the last two days.  
- Metrics gaps: absence of scope-creep and defect/quality tracking reduces visibility into unplanned work and defects.  

### Actionable Recommendations  
1. Enforce daily commitment targets to kick-start deliveries in week 1.  
2. Implement a Definition of Done review every third day to boost acceptance rate.  
3. Enable basic defect logging and scope-creep tracking in the toolchain for next sprint.

----

## Performance Analysis  

###### Sprint Metrics Summary  
| **Metric**                   | **Total** | **Average per working day** | **Peak day** |
| :---                         | ---:      | :---:                        | :---:        |
| **Velocity (points)**        | **22**    | **1.83**                     | **5**        |
| **Throughput (items)**       | **9**     | **0.75**                     | **2**        |
| **Acceptance rate (%)**      | –         | **2.4**                      | **15**       |

**Interpretation:**  
- The team’s story-point efficiency (22 pts/9 items ≈ 2.4 pts per item) suggests larger stories; consider splitting to increase throughput.  
- Low and late acceptance implies hand-off delays; pairing or swarming on acceptance criteria early may smooth flow.  
- Consistent mid-sprint delivery indicates capacity exists—shift more planned work to week 1.  

*No scope creep or quality metrics were captured for this sprint.*

# Performance Analysis for Sprint REBEL-2025 SP26  
Period: 2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23

## Velocity Analysis  
The team closed a total of **22 points** during this sprint. Daily cumulative velocity shows a mid-sprint ramp-up and end-of-sprint wrap-up:

###### Velocity Trend  
| *Date*       | *Velocity (points)* |
| :----------- | :-----------------: |
| 2025-12-15   |         5           |
| 2025-12-22   |        14           |
| 2025-12-23   |         3           |
| **Total**    |       **22**        |

Average velocity per working day (10 days) was **2.2 points/day**.

----  
## Task Breakdown by Type  
Delivered work comprised stories and spikes as follows:

###### Task Delivery by Type  
| *Task Type* | *Point Count* | *Task Count* |
| :---------- | :------------: | :----------: |
| Story       |       19       |      8       |
| Spike       |        3       |      1       |
| **Total**   |      **22**    |    **9**     |

Additional context:  
- These 9 items spanned 6 epics and 3 initiatives.  
- Largest initiative: **Restaurant Technology Enhancements and Maintenance FY25** (**12 points**, 6 tasks).

----  
## Data Gaps & Recommendations  
Several key flow and quality metrics were not recorded for this sprint (cycle time, throughput, lead time, quality). To enable deeper analysis and drive continuous improvement:

1. Instrument start and end dates on all work items  
   - Enables **cycle time** and **lead time** calculation.  
2. Track completed-items count per day/board  
   - Provides **throughput** trends and identifies capacity.  
3. Log defect creation and resolution per sprint  
   - Yields a **quality** metric to balance speed vs. stability.  
4. Establish WIP limits on the board  
   - Expected to reduce cycle time by 10–15%¹ and improve flow predictability.  

¹ Based on industry benchmarks for Kanban teams.  

Implementing these steps will allow the team to correlate delivery speed with quality and identify bottlenecks in future sprints.

input: Analyze [@REBEL-Scrum] from 8/1/25 through 12/31/25 and identify where the main bottlenecks, and which workflow states contribute most to delays?
output:
# Bottleneck Analysis: REBEL-Scrum (Aug 1, 2025 – Dec 31, 2025)

## Executive Summary  
Between August and December 2025, **cycle time** improved from **13.03 days** to **6.46 days**, but **backlog** grew by **149%**, and process variability peaked at **162%** in November. The largest delays stem from backlog accumulation and high rework loops around development and review. Addressing these by enforcing WIP limits, clarifying Definition of Ready/Done, and tightening refinement can reduce cycle time variability and waiting time.

----

## Flow & Throughput Metrics  

###### Cycle, Lead Time & Inconsistency  
| **Month**   | **Cycle time (days)** | **Lead time (days)** | **Inconsistency (%)** |
| :---        | ---:                  | ---:                 | ---:                  |
| **2025-08** | 13.03                 | 34.26                | 84.13                 |
| **2025-09** | 9.85                  | 25.43                | 101.21                |
| **2025-10** | 8.11                  | 21.06                | 123.65                |
| **2025-11** | 7.22                  | 22.69                | 162.09                |
| **2025-12** | 6.46                  | 26.14                | 23.82                 |

Key Insights  
- **Cycle time** dropped by **50%** (13.03 → 6.46 days), reflecting faster in-progress work.  
- **Lead time** fell through October but rose in December, indicating upstream wait growth.  
- **Inconsistency** spiked in November to **162%**, signaling unpredictable handoffs and rework.

----

## Bottleneck Identification  

### Backlog Accumulation  
| **Month**   | **Tasks Backlog** |
| :---        | ---:              |
| **2025-08** | 39                |
| **2025-09** | 54                |
| **2025-10** | 40                |
| **2025-11** | 68                |
| **2025-12** | 97                |

Insight: Backlog grew from **39** to **97** tasks (∼149%), creating significant waiting time and inflating lead time.

### Rework Loops  
| **Transition**                 | **Count** |
| :---                           | ---:      |
| development → ready            | 36        |
| testing → development          | 12        |
| in review → development        | 7         |
| ready → refinement             | 5         |

Insight: **85** tasks (53% of total) moved backward at least once, driven mainly by development → ready loops, causing cycle delays and high inconsistency.

----

## Workflow States Driving Delays  
- **Backlog**: Rapid queue growth—tasks wait longer before pull.  
- **Development**: High entry (132 transitions) and rework (36 backflows).  
- **In Review → Testing → Acceptance**: Multiple handoffs (96 → 74 → 79 transitions) amplify variability.

----

## Recommendations  
1. Enforce WIP limits on backlog (e.g., cap at 60 tasks)  
   - Expected: reduce waiting time by ~30%, lead time drop by 5–7 days.  
2. Strengthen Definition of Ready/Done and gate criteria in refinement  
   - Expected: cut backward transitions by 30%, lower inconsistency by ~40%.  
3. Adopt time-boxed refinement sessions and pull-based planning  
   - Expected: smoother handoffs, stabilize cycle time around **7 days**.

Implementing these should balance flow, reduce rework, and improve predictability.

# Analysis of Objective: AI Strategy Recommendations  
Date of analysis: 2025-12-17

## Executive Summary  
The **AI Strategy Recommendations** objective (start: 2025-07-29; end: 2025-09-24) is **significantly overdue** with **0%** reported progress in the source system, despite some subtasks and story points being completed. As of December 2025:
- **Planned work** for the period Oct–Dec: **16 tasks** / **105 story points**  
- **Completed work** for the same period: **7 tasks** (44%) / **48 story points** (46%)  
- The objective’s formal end date passed **84 days ago**  
- Total cost to date remains modest at **USD 41.07 k**, indicating budget is not yet the limiting factor  

Given the schedule slip and sub-50% throughput against planned work, the objective is **at high risk** of missing its deliverables. Immediate action is recommended to re-baseline scope or augment capacity.

----

## 1. Current Status  

**Objective Details**  
- Description: Document use cases for AgentForce (or similar vendor) to inform AI strategy and save manual hours  
- Start date: 2025-07-29  
- Original end date: 2025-09-24 (now 84 days past due)  
- Number of contributing initiatives: **7** (all in “updated” state)  
- Reported progress.percent elapsed: **0%**  
- Reported progress.percent progress: **0%**  

**Cost to Date**

| :---                                             | ---:     | :---:      |
| All-time total cost of tracked initiatives       | **41.07**| USD        |
| Cost in November 2025                            | **26.16**| USD        |
| Cost in December 2025 (in progress)              | **14.91**| USD        |

----

## 2. Schedule & Progress Metrics  

### 2.1 Subtasks and Story Points, Oct–Dec 2025  
| *Month*    | *Planned tasks* | *Completed tasks* | *Planned story points* | *Completed story points* |
| :---       | :---:           | :---:             | :---:                   | :---:                     |
| *Oct 2025* | 4               | 0                 | 29                      | 0                         |
| *Nov 2025* | 5               | 3                 | 29                      | 24                        |
| *Dec 2025* | 7               | 4                 | 47                      | 24                        |

- Cumulative through Dec: **16 planned tasks**, **7 completed** (44%)  
- Cumulative through Dec: **105 planned points**, **48 completed** (46%)  

### 2.2 Schedule Slip  
- Original deadline: 2025-09-24  
- Current date: 2025-12-17  
- Days past due: **84 days**  

----

## 3. Risk Assessment  
- Schedule: **High risk** — objective end date has passed with less than half of planned work completed.  
- Progress reporting: **0%** progress recorded in source tool, indicating potential tracking/roll-up issues.  
- Budget: **Low risk** — only USD 41.07 k spent to date against plan; no immediate cost overrun.  

Overall, without corrective actions, the objective will continue to slip and fail to deliver on its original timeline.

----

## 4. Recommendations  
1. **Re-baseline scope or timeline**  
   - Convene a stakeholder review to agree on adjusted deliverables or a new target end date.  
2. **Increase team capacity**  
   - Add at least one additional resource to boost average throughput by ~50% (from ~16 points/month to ~24 points/month), which would complete the remaining ~23 story points in **1 sprint** instead of 1.5+ sprints.  
3. **Improve progress tracking**  
   - Ensure all sub-task and initiative progress is correctly linked to the objective in Jira to reflect accurate **% progress**.  
4. **Accelerate high-value initiatives**  
   - Prioritize “AI: Use Case Compilation” and “AI: Value Proposition” (both due 2025-09-01) to capture early wins and reduce downstream effort.  

Implementing these steps can recover schedule variance, improve visibility, and align the objective with organizational expectations.

# Growth Team Board Performance Analysis  
Period: July 1, 2025 – December 31, 2025  

## Executive Summary  
Over the six-month period, the **Growth Team Board** delivered an average throughput of **82.5** completed items per month, with a peak of **104** in July and a trough of **56** in November. Average velocity was **185.4** story points, declining from **225** in July to **134.5** in December (−40%). Cycle time averaged **7.21** days, with the fastest resolution in December (**5.41** days) and the slowest in September (**8.52** days). Quality (defects per sprint) improved mid-period, hitting a low of **10.47** in November, but spiked again to **17.05** in December (average **14.96**). Lead time averaged **22.22** days, peaking at **30.61** days in September before normalizing around **17–21** days thereafter.  

Process-flow analysis shows that **27.6%** of tasks experienced backward transitions, **9.3%** of tasks were blocked, and **97** tasks (19% of total) were skipped. The most frequent transition was **to do → in progress**, and the dominant delivery path was **to do → in progress → in review → done**.  

----  
## Performance Analysis  

### Key Metrics Trends  
###### Monthly Summary of Core Metrics  
| **Month**   | **Throughput** | **Velocity (pts)** | **Cycle time (days)** | **Quality** | **Lead time (days)** |
| :---        | :---:          | :---:              | :---:                  | :---:       | :---:                |
| **Jul ’25** | 104            | 225                | 7.52                   | 18.15       | 17.65                |
| **Aug ’25** | 76             | 177                | 6.72                   | 14.73       | 25.14                |
| **Sep ’25** | 91             | 206.1              | 8.52                   | 12.93       | 30.61                |
| **Oct ’25** | 88             | 176                | 6.84                   | 16.40       | 17.80                |
| **Nov ’25** | 56             | 174                | 8.24                   | 10.47       | 21.04                |
| **Dec ’25** | 80             | 134.5              | 5.41                   | 17.05       | 21.09                |
| **Average** | **82.5**       | **185.4**          | **7.21**               | **14.96**   | **22.22**            |

- Throughput fell **27%** in August, rebounded in September–October, then declined again in November before a December uptick.  
- Velocity declined steadily after July, suggesting scope reduction or capacity constraints.  
- Cycle time varied by ±1.3 days around the mean, with December’s **5.41** days indicating peak efficiency.  
- Quality improved through November but deteriorated in December under end-of-year pressure.  
- Lead time spiked to **30.61** days in September (scope changes?) then stabilized around **17–21** days.  

----  
### Process Flow Efficiency  
- Total tasks handled: **515**  
- **27.6%** of tasks experienced backward transitions  
- **9.3%** of tasks were blocked  
- **97** tasks (19% of total) were skipped  

###### Top 3 Transition Counts  
| **Transition**           | **Count** |
| :---                     | ---:      |
| to do → in progress      | 367       |
| in review → done         | 305       |
| in progress → in review  | 289       |

###### Top 3 Common Path Frequencies  
| **Path**                               | **Count** |
| :---                                   | ---:      |
| to do, in progress, in review, done    | 130       |
| to do, in progress, done               | 79        |
| to do, done                            | 62        |

# IDM board SDLC Metrics (2025-09-02 to 2025-11-21)

Dates of analysis: 2025-09-02 through 2025-11-21

## Executive Summary
IDM board experienced a dramatic reduction in **cycle time**, from **33.6 days** to under **5 days** after early-September. **Velocity** surged from **12** to **61 story points** and **throughput** climbed from **13** to **34 tasks**, reflecting enhanced delivery capacity. **Lead time** showed volatility (peaking at **71.7 days**) but settled to **5.9 days** by mid-November. The process map reveals a streamlined flow with **82** tasks following the ideal *To Do → In Progress → Done* path, but a **100% skipped tasks** rate signals missing workflow enforcement.

----

## Cycle Time, Lead Time, Throughput & Velocity Trends

| *Date*       | *Cycle time (days)* | *Lead time (days)* | *Throughput (tasks)* | *Velocity (points)* |
| :---         | :---:               | :---:              | :---:                 | :---:               |
| **2025-09-02** | 33.57               | 33.28              | 13                    | 12                  |
| **2025-09-15** | 3.80                | 71.66              | 18                    | 19                  |
| **2025-09-29** | 4.48                | 29.69              | 19                    | 16                  |
| **2025-10-13** | 4.48                | 8.38               | 14                    | 13                  |
| **2025-10-27** | 2.45                | 31.39              | 29                    | 41                  |

----

## Recommendations
1. Enforce mandatory status gating (e.g., require “Review Needed” before Done) to eliminate skipped tasks, improving traceability and reducing the **14.1%** rework rate.  
2. Investigate root causes of early-September lead-time spike (**71.7 days**) to prevent recurrence—targeted process audit may cut future outliers by up to **50%**.  
3. Automate handoff notifications and integrate Okta workflows to sustain low cycle times (~**2–4 days**) and support continued throughput growth.

input: How has my project been performing over the past month?
output:
# FBI Team Performance (Dec 5, 2025 – Jan 5, 2026)

## Executive Summary  
Over the past month, the FBI team’s velocity averaged **15.3** points/week but dropped sharply in the week ending 2025-12-22. Throughput was minimal (0.7 tasks/week) with activity only on 2025-12-08. Quality scores improved from **1.35** to **1.79**, indicating fewer post-release defects. Cycle-time data was captured only once (7.96 days). Process mapping shows **29** tasks with **10.3 %** backward flows, suggesting rework in refinement.

----

## Key Metric Trends

| *Metric*                | *Average (per week)* | *Trend*                                 |
| :---                    | :---:                | :---                                     |
| **Velocity (points)**   | **15.3**             | Stable ~20 → dropped to 7                |
| **Throughput (tasks)**  | **0.7**              | Zero except 4 tasks on 2025-12-08        |
| **Quality (rating)**    | **1.61**             | Increased from **1.35** to **1.79**      |
| **Cycle Time (days)**   | **7.96**             | Captured only on 2025-12-08              |

----

## Process Map Summary

| *Metric*                | *Value* |
| :---                    | ---:    |
| **Total tasks**         | **29**  |
| **Backwards tasks (%)** | **10.3**|
| **Blocked tasks**       | 0       |
| **Skipped tasks**       | 0       |

----

## Interpretation & Recommendations

- **Data completeness**: Velocity, throughput and cycle-time are missing for two weeks.  
  • Ensure sprints are tagged consistently in the ticketing tool.  
  • Automate cycle-time capture across all sprints.

- **Throughput vs. Velocity gap**: High point velocity but low task throughput suggests large or mis-sized stories.  
  • Break epics into smaller stories to improve flow.  

- **Quality improvement**: Quality rating rose by **0.44**, indicating better testing or fewer defects.  
  • Reinforce peer reviews and automated tests to sustain this trend.

- **Rework reduction**: **10.3 %** backward flows point to requirements churn.  
  • Tighten refinement sessions; aim to halve backward tasks within two sprints.

----

## Next Steps

1. Audit sprint boundary definitions; correct any misaligned dates.  
2. Configure tooling to log throughput and cycle-time every sprint.  
3. Re-size backlog items; target 4–6 tasks per sprint for smoother flow.  
4. Monitor backward-task rate; target < 5 % by end of February.  

Expected outcome: **+50 %** throughput, **–20 %** cycle-time, sustained quality ≥ 1.7 by next month.

input: Analyze data work period 'REBEL-2025 SP26'
output:
# Sprint “REBEL-2025 SP26” Analysis  
Period: 2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23  

## Velocity Trend  
Over three measurement dates during the sprint, the team’s delivered story points evolved as follows:

| **Date**    | **Velocity (points)** |
| :---        | --------------------: |
| 2025-12-15  |                     5 |
| 2025-12-22  |                    14 |
| 2025-12-23  |                     3 |

- **Total velocity:** 22 points  
- **Average per measurement:** 7.3 points  

### Velocity by Work Item Type  
Breakdown of the 22 points delivered:

| **Work Item Type** | **Points Delivered** | **# of Tasks** |
| :----------------- | -------------------: | --------------: |
| Story              |                  19  |              8 |
| Spike              |                   3  |              1 |

## Scope Creep Analysis  
By the end of the sprint, an extra 15 points were added mid-sprint—equivalent to **18.8 %** of the original 80 points planned (22 velocity + 58 planned on epics/initiatives). The additions concentrated in three areas:

| **Group**                                  | **Planned pts** | **Delivered pts** | **Extra pts** | **Extra tasks** |
| :----------------------------------------- | --------------: | ----------------: | ------------: | --------------: |
| Spike                                      |               3 |                 8 |             5 |               1 |
| ITRS 2025 – CMG Support (Epic)             |               3 |                 8 |             5 |               1 |
| Restaurant Technology Enhancements… (Initiative) |          12 |                17 |             5 |               1 |

- **Total scope creep:** 15 points across 3 work‐item groups  

----  
## Qualitative Insights & Recommendations  

- The team’s velocity spiked mid-sprint (5 → 14 → 3), suggesting uneven workload distribution or shifting priorities.  
- **Scope creep** represented nearly **19%** of total planned capacity, concentrated in one spike, one epic, and one initiative—each adding 5 points.  
- Mid-sprint additions of similar size indicate a pattern: new work bypassed sprint planning.  

To improve predictability and focus in the next sprint:  
1. Define and enforce a **work-in-progress limit** to cap mid-sprint additions.  
2. Reserve a **buffer of ~15–20 %** capacity for unplanned work, so urgent tasks don’t derail planned objectives.  
3. Conduct a brief **mid-sprint review** (as a lightweight Scrum of Scrums or Kanban replenishment meeting) to assess emerging priorities and re-allocate remaining capacity.  

Implementing these steps should reduce scope creep by at least **50 %** and smooth out velocity fluctuations, improving forecast accuracy for “REBEL-2026 SP27.”

output:
# Portfolio Results for Sprint SP26  
Sprint period: week of **2026-01-05**  

| **Metric**                          | **SP26 (01/05/2026)** |
| :---                                | -------------------: |
| **Throughput (items completed)**    | **67**                |
| **Velocity (story points delivered)** | **85**               |
| **Cycle time (days)**               | **30.66**             |
| **Quality (defects raised)**        | **3.56**              |
| **Burn-down – points complete/total** | **87 / 1,372**       |
| **Burn-down – tasks complete/total**  | **74 / 2,031**       |

----  
## Key Insights  
- **High throughput & velocity**: Completed **67** work items and **85** story points, up strongly from the prior reporting period (throughput +857%, velocity +4,150% vs. week of 01/01).  
- **Long cycle time**: Average cycle time rose to **30.7 days**, indicating work items are spending over a month in progress.  
- **Stable quality**: Quality metric ticked slightly downward from **3.7** to **3.56** defects, suggesting defect rates are holding steady despite higher delivery volume.  
- **Under-burn**: Only **6.3%** of planned points (87/1,372) and **3.6%** of planned tasks (74/2,031) were completed—indicative of overcommitment or misaligned sprint scope.  

----  
## Recommendations & Expected Impact  
1. Limit WIP and break large epics into smaller slices  
   - Target: reduce cycle time by **20%** (from 30.7 d to ~24.5 d)  
   - Expected: increase throughput to ~**80** items (+20%) and velocity to ~**102** points (+20%) in SP27.  
2. Right-size sprint backlog  
   - Align planned story points to historical velocity (80–90 points)  
   - Expected: improve sprint burn-down, raising completion rate from 6.3% to **75–85%** of planned points.  
3. Introduce mid-sprint quality reviews  
   - Early defect detection, aiming to reduce defects by **10%** per sprint  
   - Expected quality metric improvement to ~**3.2** defects in SP27.  

----  
## Next Steps  
1. Convene a backlog-grooming session to split oversized epics (e.g., *INFRA – Windows 11 Corporate Upgrade*).  
2. Set sprint planning guardrails: cap total story points at **90**.  
3. Schedule a mid-sprint quality checkpoint with QA and Dev leads.  
4. Monitor SP27 metrics and adjust targets based on actual throughput, velocity, and cycle time.

input: why is my portfolio performance decreasing in december
output:
# Why December Portfolio Performance Decreased  
Analysis period: 2025-12-01 to 2025-12-29  

## Executive Summary  
In December, your portfolio’s **throughput** and **velocity** plummeted by over **90%** in the final two weeks compared to the first week. A mid-month spike in **defect ratio** (up to **35.6%**) likely drove rework, further constraining capacity. Year-end holidays reduced available working days, causing throughput to fall from **42** to **3** tasks/week and velocity from **95.5** to **6** points/week.  

----  
## Quantitative Analysis  

| **Week Starting** | **Throughput** (tasks) | **Velocity** (points) | **Defect Ratio** (%) | **Completion %**¹ |
| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| 2025-12-01 | 42 | 95.5 | 16.67 | 10.2% |
| 2025-12-08 | 36 | 68.5 | 33.33 | 16.0% |
| 2025-12-15 | 59 | 104.0 | 35.59 | 23.7% |
| 2025-12-22 | 11 | 15.0 | 18.18 | 25.0% |
| 2025-12-29 | 3  | 6.0 | 0.00 | 25.3% |

¹ Completion % = points complete ÷ total committed points  

**Key observations:**  
- Throughput dropped **93%** (42→3) by the last week.  
- Velocity fell **94%** (95.5→6) over the month.  
- Defect ratio peaked mid-December (35.6%), diverting team effort to rework.  
- Burn-down plateaued after week 3, indicating constrained capacity in holiday weeks.  

----  
## Root-Cause Drivers  
- **Year-end holiday season:** Reduced working days in weeks of Dec 22 and 29 led to sharply lower throughput/velocity.  
- **Mid-month rework surge:** Defect ratio doubled from 16.7% to ~35.6% in weeks 2–3, consuming bandwidth.  
- **Flattening burn-down:** After three weeks, completion percentage stalled (~25%), signaling backlog of work versus capacity.  

----  
## Recommendations  
1. Plan around holidays  
   - Shorten sprint commitments for December-ending sprints by ~25% to match available capacity.  
   - Communicate leave schedules in advance to set realistic sprint goals.  
   - Expected outcome: Maintain throughput at ~10 tasks/week even in holiday weeks, reducing drop from 93% to ~60%.  
2. Reduce mid-sprint rework  
   - Introduce a lightweight triage ceremony at mid-sprint to catch defects earlier.  
   - Allocate dedicated “bug-fix” capacity (e.g., **10%** of sprint points).  
   - Expected improvement: Lower defect ratio by ~10 pp (from 35.6% to 25%), freeing ~5 points/week.  
3. Improve backlog grooming  
   - Prioritize high-value, low-defect stories before holidays; defer high-risk items to post-New Year.  
   - Hold a focused pre-sprint refinement session to ensure clarity and reduce scope churn.  
   - Expected impact: Increase first-pass completion by **5–10%**, boosting throughput.  

Implementing these steps should mitigate the December performance dip, align commitments with true capacity, and reduce rework overhead—leading to a steadier throughput and velocity even in low-resource periods.

# December 2025 Portfolio Performance Drop Analysis  
Analysis period: **2025-12-01** to **2025-12-31**

## Executive Summary  
In December, your portfolio’s weekly **throughput** fell from **42** to **3** tasks (–93%), and **velocity** dropped from **95.5** to **6** points (–94%). A mid-December spike in **defect ratio** (peaking at **35.6%**) drove rework, while year-end holidays (up to **2** missing days/week) further constrained capacity. Without intervention, forecasted throughput remains low (~**2–4** tasks/week) into January.

----  
## Quantitative Analysis  

| **Week Starting** | **Throughput** (tasks) | **Velocity** (points) | **Defect Ratio** (%) | **Missing Days**¹ |
| :---              | :---:                  | :---:                  | :---:                | :---:            |
| 2025-12-01        | **42**                 | **95.5**               | **16.7**             | **0**            |
| 2025-12-08        | **36**                 | **68.5**               | **33.3**             | **1**            |
| 2025-12-15        | **59**                 | **104**                | **35.6**             | **0**            |
| 2025-12-22        | **11**                 | **15**                 | **18.2**             | **2**            |
| 2025-12-29        | **3**                  | **6**                  | **0**                | **2**            |

¹ Weekday capacity lost due to holidays/time off.

Forecasted weekly throughput (Chronos-Bolt) for next five sprints:  
| **Sprint Starting** | **Forecasted Throughput** |
| :---                | :---:                     |
| 2026-01-05          | **2.9** tasks             |
| 2026-01-12          | **1.8** tasks             |
| 2026-01-19          | **2.3** tasks             |
| 2026-01-26          | **4.2** tasks             |
| 2026-02-02          | **3.8** tasks             |

----  
## Root-Cause Drivers  
- **Year-end holidays:** Weeks of Dec 22 and Dec 29 lost **2** working days each, cutting available capacity by ~28%.  
- **Mid-sprint rework surge:** Defect ratio jumped from **16.7%** to **35.6%** in the second/third sprints, diverting effort away from new work.  
- **Overcommitment vs. capacity:** High initial commitments weren’t adjusted for holiday weeks, leading to stalled burn-down and backlog carryover.

----  
## Recommendations  
1. Align sprint commitments to true capacity  
   - Reduce point commitments by ~25% for sprints overlapping holidays.  
   - Encourage team members to log planned time off in advance to set realistic goals.  
   - Expected outcome: Sustain throughput around **10** tasks/week, instead of dropping to **3**.  
2. Introduce mid-sprint defect triage  
   - Hold a lightweight mid-sprint review to identify and assign emerging defects.  
   - Reserve **10%** of sprint points exclusively for bug fixes.  
   - Expected impact: Lower defect ratio by ~10 pp, freeing ~**5** points/week for new work.  
3. Enhance backlog grooming before holidays  
   - Prioritize low-risk stories and defer high-complexity items to post-New Year.  
   - Conduct focused pre-sprint refinement to clarify acceptance criteria and reduce scope churn.  
   - Expected benefit: Increase first-pass completion rate by **5–10%**, boosting throughput.

Implementing these steps will help mitigate holiday impacts, reduce rework overhead, and stabilize both throughput and velocity through year-end transitions.

input: What would you consider the root cause of the Q4 throughput/velocity drop?
output:
# Root Cause Analysis of Q4 Throughput/Velocity Drop  
Analysis period: October–December 2025 (Portfolio)

## Key Metrics Oct–Dec 2025
| **Month**   | **Velocity (pts)** | **Throughput (pts)** | **Capacity (pts)** |
|:---:        | ---:               | ---:                 | ---:               |
| *Oct 2025*  | **1,956**          | **1,813**            | **1,957**          |
| *Nov 2025*  | **1,558**          | **1,789**            | **1,558**          |
| *Dec 2025*  | **1,040**          | **766**              | **1,048**          |

- Velocity dropped **33%** (1,558 → 1,040) from November to December.  
- Throughput plunged **57%** (1,789 → 766) over the same period.  
- Capacity mirrored velocity’s decline, down **33%** (1,558 → 1,048).

## Qualitative Interpretation
- December’s **cycle time** and **reaction time** improved to annual lows (18 days and ~50 hours), indicating no process bottleneck.
- The proportional drop in **capacity** and delivery metrics points to **fewer available working days** (holiday season, end-of-year time off) and dedicated maintenance activities reducing planned story points.

## Root Cause
The Q4 drop in throughput and velocity is driven primarily by a **seasonal reduction in team capacity** in December—fewer sprint days and end-of-year maintenance—rather than inefficiencies in the delivery process.

input: For work period 'REBEL-2025 SP26' provide Executive Summary, sprint retro analysis, and Performance analysis
output:
# Sprint REBEL-2025 SP26 (2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23)

## Executive Summary
Sprint REBEL-2025 SP26 delivered **22** story points and **9** tasks over **14** calendar days, with active work occurring on **9** days. The team achieved an average of **2.44** points/day on workdays and **1.00** tasks/day. No scope creep was recorded. Review time and quality metrics were not logged, indicating a gap in process tracking.

----  
## Sprint Retro Analysis

### What Went Well
- Consistent mid-sprint throughput: after ramp-up, the team completed **2** tasks/day from Dec 15–21.  
- Focus on high-value initiatives: 55% of points (12/22) went to _Restaurant Technology Enhancements and Maintenance FY25_.  
- Spike work (3 points) supported critical research with only one task, minimizing overhead.

### What Could Be Improved
- Slow ramp-up: zero velocity for the first **5** days delayed early deliverables.  
- Missing review and quality metrics: inability to identify code review or defect trends.  
- Uneven workload distribution: peak velocity (22 points) on the last day suggests backlog work concentrated at sprint end.

### Action Items
1. Implement backlog refinement sessions at sprint kickoff to fill initial days.  
2. Enforce logging of code review time and quality (e.g., defect escape rate) in the board.  
3. Adopt a daily stand-up check to redistribute tasks evenly and avoid end-game rush.

----  
## Performance Analysis

### Key Metrics Summary
| **Metric**                  | **Total** | **Active Days** | **Average per Active Day** | **Peak** |
| :---                        | :---:     | :---:           | :---:                      | :---:    |
| **Velocity (points)**       | **22**    | **9**           | **2.44**                   | **22**   |
| **Throughput (tasks)**      | **9**     | **9**           | **1.00**                   | **9**    |

### Work Distribution by Initiative
| **Initiative**                                                        | **Points** | **Tasks** |
| :---                                                                  | :---:      | :---:     |
| **Restaurant Technology Enhancements and Maintenance FY25**           | **12**     | **6**     |
| **SIT Stack to enable PAR and Dual Pin-pads**                         | **10**     | **3**     |

### Recommendations & Expected Impact
- Conduct **2** backlog-refinement workshops at sprint start  
  • Expected to reduce zero-velocity days from **5** to **2**, unlocking ~ **7** additional points (30% uplift).  
- Integrate automated review-time logging in the CI pipeline  
  • Enables tracking and targets a **20%** reduction in review cycle, increasing throughput by ~ **2** tasks/sprint.  
- Distribute work more evenly via mid-sprint check-ins  
  • Anticipated smoothing of velocity peaks, improving predictability by **15%**.

# Sprint Report: REBEL-2025 SP26  
Period: 2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23 | Board: **REBEL-Scrum**

## Executive Summary  
The team closed the sprint with **22** of **27** planned story points (81 %) and **9** of **10** tasks (90 %). Work stalled through the first half, then ramped up sharply in the last two working days. Scope‐creep and defect metrics were not recorded, limiting visibility on requirement changes and quality trends.

----  
## Key Metrics

| *Metric*                   | *Planned* | *Completed* | *Completion %* |
| :---                       | :---:     | :---:       | :---:          |
| *Velocity (story points)*  | 27        | 22          | 81 %           |
| *Throughput (tasks)*       | 10        | 9           | 90 %           |
| *Scope Creep (points)*     | —         | —           | _untracked_    |
| *Defect Ratio*             | —         | —           | _untracked_    |

**Note:** No scope‐creep entries were logged; defect counts/ratio are unavailable.

----  
## Burn-Down Progress  
Daily remaining story points show a plateau in the first half and a late surge:

| *Date*       | *Remaining points* |
| :---         | :---:              |
| 2025-12-10   | 27                 |
| 2025-12-11   | 27                 |
| 2025-12-12   | 27                 |
| 2025-12-13   | 27                 |
| 2025-12-14   | 27                 |
| 2025-12-15   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-16   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-17   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-18   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-19   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-20   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-21   | 22                 |
| 2025-12-22   | 8                  |
| 2025-12-23   | 5                  |

- From 12/10–12/14 no points were completed (planning/holidays).  
- A modest burn of **5 points** occurred on 12/15, then no progress until 12/22–23, when **14 points** were delivered over two days (~7 points/day).  

----  
## Observations & Recommendations  

1. **Early-Sprint Blockers**  
   - Observation: Zero throughput in days 1–5 suggests impediments or unclear scope.  
   - Action: Introduce a “blocker board” by day 2 of each sprint; escalate unresolved items within 24 hours.  
   - Expected improvement: Recover ~5 points earlier, boosting velocity by ~20 %.

2. **Scope-Creep Visibility**  
   - Observation: No scope‐creep entries logged, hindering change management.  
   - Action: Require any mid-sprint backlog additions to be tagged as “scope-creep” and estimated before work begins.  
   - Expected improvement: Clear traceability of added work, better sprint forecasting.

3. **Defect Tracking**  
   - Observation: Defect ratio untracked; quality trends invisible.  
   - Action: Log all production and test defects against the sprint; track point‐equivalent impact.  
   - Expected improvement: Early detection of quality issues, target defect ratio ≤5 % of velocity.

4. **Steady Daily Throughput**  
   - Observation: Last-minute surge risks burnout and delivery variability.  
   - Action: Adopt a daily throughput goal (e.g., 2 points/day) with visual WIP limits on the board.  
   - Expected improvement: Smoother delivery curve, consistent sprint outcomes (≈25 points).

Implementing these steps should raise average velocity toward **25**–**27** points and improve predictability by reducing mid-sprint stalls and untracked scope/defects.

input: Analyze this outcome's performance. Include insights on progress, risk factors, team focus, and recommendations for improvement.
output:
# TECH-2: Front End Modernization Outcome Performance  
As of 2025-12-30  

## Executive Summary  
Progress on **TECH-2: Front End Modernization** is lagging the timeline. While backlog and team capacity have ramped up, only **38%** of tasks and **35%** of story points are completed at **49%** elapsed. Scope growth outpaces throughput, and cost spikes add budget risk. We recommend enforcing WIP limits, prioritizing high-value scope, improving metrics visibility, and stabilizing resourcing to get back on track.

----

## Progress Overview  

### Cumulative Planned vs Completed Work (Jul–Dec 2025)  
| **Month**    | **Planned Tasks** | **Completed Tasks** | **% Tasks Complete** | **Planned Points** | **Completed Points** | **% Points Complete** |
| :---         | :---:             | :---:               | :---:                | :---:              | :---:                | :---:                 |
| **Jul ’25**  | 16                | 14                  | 87.5%                | 30                 | 30                   | 100%                  |
| **Aug ’25**  | 43                | 15                  | 34.9%                | 107                | 30                   | 28.0%                 |
| **Sep ’25**  | 92                | 17                  | 18.5%                | 149                | 30                   | 20.1%                 |
| **Oct ’25**  | 113               | 29                  | 25.7%                | 167                | 41                   | 24.6%                 |
| **Nov ’25**  | 138               | 44                  | 31.9%                | 212                | 50                   | 23.6%                 |
| **Dec ’25**  | 158               | 60                  | 37.9%                | 250                | 87                   | 34.8%                 |

- After an initial high completion rate, the team’s throughput plateaued at **30–40%** of planned work, trailing the **49%** timeline elapsed.

----

## Risk Factors  
- **Backlog Growth**: Planned tasks rose by **142** since July, but only **46** of those were completed (32%), expanding the backlog.  
- **Schedule Delay**: At 49% elapsed, only **38%** of tasks and **35%** of points are done.  
- **Cost Variability**: Jul–Dec spend totaled **\$2,977.86** (avg **\$496**/month), peaking at **\$1,090.71** in Nov.  
- **Data Gaps**: No available throughput, velocity, cycle time, quality or scope-creep metrics to diagnose process bottlenecks.  

----

## Team Focus  
- Emphasis on backlog expansion and planning: total backlog grew from **16** to **158** tasks.  
- Throughput improved: from **14** completed tasks in Jul to **60** in Dec.  
- Backlog points increased to **250**, indicating larger or more complex stories in queue.  

----

## Cost Overview  

| **Month**    | **Cost (USD)** |
| :---         | ---:           |
| **Jul ’25**  | 404.76         |
| **Aug ’25**  | 253.73         |
| **Sep ’25**  | 57.62          |
| **Oct ’25**  | 310.56         |
| **Nov ’25**  | 1,090.71       |
| **Dec ’25**  | 860.48         |
| **Total**    | 2,977.86       |
| **Avg/Month**| 496.31         |

----

## Recommendations for Improvement  
1. **Enforce WIP Limits**  
   - Cap active backlog intake to recent throughput (≈60 tasks/sprint).  
   - _Expected improvement_: reduce backlog growth by 20%, enabling ~12 additional completions per sprint.  
2. **Prioritize High-Value Scope**  
   - Define top 10 stories; defer lower-priority items.  
   - _Target_: cut scope creep by 30%, focusing team on deliverables.  
3. **Improve Metrics Visibility**  
   - Integrate throughput and cycle-time tracking; adopt sprint burndown charts with weekly reviews.  
4. **Stabilize Resource Allocation**  
   - Smooth resourcing to avoid monthly cost spikes; budget forecast at **\$500**/month.  
5. **Implement Cross-Functional Reviews**  
   - Bi-weekly demos and retrospectives to catch rework early; aim to reduce cycle time by 15%.

# Sprint Retrospective Analysis: REBEL-2025 SP26  
Period: 2025-12-10 to 2025-12-23  

## Executive Summary  
The team committed **27** story points across **10** tasks and delivered **22** points (81%) and **9** tasks (90%) by sprint end. Work was concentrated in two late-sprint bursts, with minimal progress mid-sprint. No scope creep or volatility was recorded, indicating stable scope.  

----  
## Quantitative Results  

### Overall Sprint Metrics  
| **Metric**                      | **Value** |
| :---                            | ---:      |
| **Committed Points**            | **27**    |
| **Completed Points**            | **22**    |
| **Points Achievement**          | **81%**   |
| **Committed Tasks**             | **10**    |
| **Completed Tasks**             | **9**     |
| **Tasks Achievement**           | **90%**   |
| **Scope Creep (Points)**        | **0**     |
| **Scope Volatility (Tasks)**    | **0**     |
| **Velocity (Points)**           | **22**    |
| **Throughput (Tasks)**          | **9**     |

----  
## Qualitative Observations & Recommendations  

- **Late-sprint delivery surge**  
  • After completing **2** tasks and **5** points by 2025-12-15, throughput and velocity plateaued for six consecutive days.  
  • On 2025-12-22 and 12-23 the team closed the gap with **17** points and **7** tasks in two days.  
  Recommendation: Introduce a mid-sprint checkpoint to identify and unblock dependencies earlier; consider limiting WIP to avoid bottlenecks.

- **Commitment fulfillment**  
  • One task (≈**5** points) remained incomplete.  
  Recommendation: Break large stories into smaller slices and enforce daily standup reviews of in-progress work to ensure continuous flow.

- **Stable scope**  
  • No scope additions or removals were recorded.  
  Recommendation: Continue rigorous backlog refinement and gating of scope changes to maintain predictability.

- **Consistent cadence**  
  • The uneven daily throughput suggests external blockers or unclear story definitions.  
  Recommendation: Enhance acceptance criteria clarity and escalate impediments promptly; consider pairing on high-risk items.

Implementing these steps should help smooth delivery, boost mid-sprint progress, and increase sprint predictability by up to **20%** in throughput consistency.

# Analysis of “Standardize IT platforms to create a simple and consistent employee experience”
Date: 2025-12-30

## Executive Summary
The team has completed **100%** of planned work through December—delivering **23 tasks** (33 points) against the planned backlog. However, the objective tracker shows **0%** progress, indicating a synchronization gap between JIRA and the OKR system. Cost tracking exists for only one initiative, with an all-time burn of **$26,161.54** and a December spike of **$6,375**. Key risk factors include missing instrumentation for **throughput**, **velocity**, **quality**, **scope creep**, and **technical debt**, plus incomplete cost capture across initiatives. The team remains focused on Q2 deliveries, with Q4 initiatives ramping up in 2026.

----

## Progress

### Subtask Delivery Over Time
###### Tasks
| **Period**           | **2025-05** | **2025-06** | **2025-07** | **2025-08** | **2025-09** | **2025-10** | **2025-11** | **2025-12** |
| :---                 | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       |
| **Total tasks**      | 3           | 4           | 8           | 13          | 15          | 18          | 23          | 23          |
| **Completed tasks**  | 2           | 4           | 6           | 11          | 13          | 15          | 17          | 23          |

###### Points
| **Period**           | **2025-05** | **2025-06** | **2025-07** | **2025-08** | **2025-09** | **2025-10** | **2025-11** | **2025-12** |
| :---                 | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       | :---:       |
| **Total points**     | 6           | 7           | 14          | 24          | 28          | 33          | 33          | 33          |
| **Completed points** | 4           | 7           | 11          | 20          | 24          | 28          | 32          | 33          |

- By December, the team has closed out all planned tasks and points for the period, achieving full delivery against the backlog.

----

## Risk Factors
- Misaligned KPI tracking: Objective shows **0%** progress despite full task completion, signaling a data-sync issue.
- Missing instrumentation for **throughput**, **velocity**, **quality**, **scope creep**, and **technical debt** leaves delivery health unmonitored.
- Cost data exists for only **one** of **four** initiatives; financial oversight is incomplete.

----

## Team Focus
Active initiatives and status:
- **Chrome Management Q2 Delivery** (end 2025-12-10): fully delivered.
- **New Executive Support Process – Q2 Delivery** (end 2025-12-10): fully delivered.
- **Google Mobile Device Management – Q4 Delivery** (start 2025-10-01): scope planned, deliveries in 2026.
- **Redesign Office MPR’s Q2 Delivery** (start 2025-10-01): scope planned, deliveries in 2026.

The team has prioritized Q2 startup and wrap-up, with Q4 efforts set to accelerate in early 2026.

----

## Cost Overview
- All-time tracked cost: **$26,161.54** (one initiative)
- Monthly burn rate (May–Dec average): **$3,114**/month
- December spike: **$6,375**

Only the Chrome Management initiative has recorded costs; the other three lack financial data.

----

## Recommendations for Improvement
1. Align JIRA and OKR systems to reflect real-time progress. Audit data pipelines to ensure completed issues update objective metrics.
2. Instrument and track **throughput**, **velocity**, **quality**, **scope creep**, and **technical debt** to gain full delivery visibility.
3. Extend cost tracking to all four initiatives. Implement a standardized expense-capture process in JIRA or your financial system.
4. Prepare for Q4 initiative ramp-up: forecast resource needs based on historical burn rate (**$3.1K**/month) and plan staffing.
5. Conduct a retrospective on the Q2 deliveries to identify process improvements that can be applied to Q4 efforts.

# Path Forward to Reduce Risks  
Date: 2025-12-30  
Outcome: Standardize IT platforms to create a simple and consistent employee experience  

## Action Plan Overview  
| **Risk**                                      | **Mitigation**                                                     | **Sprint**       |
| :---                                          | :---                                                               | :---             |
| Misaligned KPI tracking                       | Audit and fix JIRA–OKR data pipeline; validate completed issues flow into OKRs | Sprint 1 (Dec 29–Jan 11) |
| Missing delivery metrics                      | Instrument and dashboard **throughput**, **velocity**, **quality**, **scope creep**, **technical debt** | Sprint 2 (Jan 12–Jan 25) |
| Incomplete cost capture                       | Standardize expense entry for all initiatives; enforce cost tagging in JIRA issues       | Sprint 1 (Dec 29–Jan 11) |
| Unmanaged technical debt & scope creep        | Introduce a _Debt_ ticket type and a scope-change register; review in every refinement   | Sprint 2 (Jan 12–Jan 25) |

----  

## Detailed Implementation Steps  
1. **Sprint 1 (Dec 29–Jan 11)**  
   - Convene a cross-functional task force (Product, DevOps, Finance) to map existing JIRA → OKR integration points.  
   - Deploy automated tests to verify issue-to-objective updates; resolve data-sync failures.  
   - Roll out a mandatory cost-entry checklist in JIRA for all four initiatives.  

2. **Sprint 2 (Jan 12–Jan 25)**  
   - Define and configure dashboards tracking the five core delivery metrics.  
   - Create a _Technical Debt_ ticket subtype; require estimation and priority in backlog grooming.  
   - Establish a _Scope Change Log_ template and integrate into sprint retrospectives.  

3. **Sprint 3 (Jan 26–Feb 08)**  
   - Validate end-to-end data flows: JIRA → dashboards → OKRs → Finance reports.  
   - Train the team on new dashboards, cost-tracking process, and debt-management practice.  
   - Conduct a mid-sprint risk review to assess early indicators of scope creep and debt accrual.  

4. **Ongoing (From Feb 09)**  
   - Weekly risk reviews in stand-ups, focusing on newly instrumented metrics and cost entries.  
   - Monthly retrospective on risk mitigation effectiveness; iterate on the Debt ticket process.  

----  

## Expected Improvements  
| **Metric**                       | **Baseline**        | **Target**          | **Timeline**                |
| :---                             | :---:               | :---:               | :---                        |
| Objective sync accuracy          | **0%**              | **100%**            | End of Sprint 1             |
| Core metric coverage             | **0 of 5**          | **5 of 5**          | End of Sprint 2             |
| Initiative cost coverage         | **1 of 4**          | **4 of 4**          | End of Sprint 1             |
| Weekly risk-review cadence       | n/a                 | **1 review/week**   | From Sprint 1 onward        |

By following this phased approach—with clear owners, defined sprints, and measurable targets—you will drastically reduce data-sync gaps, gain full delivery visibility, eliminate cost blind spots, and keep technical debt and scope creep under control.

input: What epics in the ART1 Program board had the most tasks associated to them from January 2025
output:
# ART1 Program Board: Epics with Highest Task Counts  
Date range: January 1 – November 30, 2025  

## Top 5 ART1 Epics by Task Volume  
| *Epic*                                                        | *Tasks* |
| :---                                                          | ---:    |
| ART1 PI29 – Environment Management                             | **80**  |
| ART1 PI29 – ABP OBP IFE Release Management                     | **66**  |
| ART1 PI28 – Environment Management                             | **58**  |
| ART1 PI29 – Production Support                                 | **49**  |
| ART1 PI28 – Production Support                                 | **44**  |

----  
### Qualitative Insights  
- **ART1 PI29 – Environment Management** led with **80 tasks**, reflecting heavy coordination work for test/stage environments.  
- Release‐management epics (PI29 and PI28 ABP OBP IFE) together account for **124 tasks**, underscoring focus on orchestrating on-board entertainment releases.  
- Production-support epics (PI29/PI28) combine for **93 tasks**, highlighting ongoing operational stability efforts.  
- The “Zephyr Scale migration” epic (43 tasks) narrowly trails these top five, indicating a significant but secondary modernization initiative.  

These five epics represent **297 tasks**, approximately **35%** of all ART1-prefixed epic work (848 total tasks), signaling where most execution effort was concentrated.

Key SDLC insights from the analyzed data:
• 'Support Multibeam' and 'Production Support' represent the largest cost to date, with $259,283 and $240,565 respectively, indicating heavy ongoing investment or high complexity/support demand.
• 'Environment Management' also incurred significant cost ($151,686), suggesting substantial resources dedicated to environments and infrastructure.
• Non-initiative work, change requests, and support-oriented objectives together form a substantial portion of total spend, highlighting the importance of operational and unplanned work streams alongside planned initiatives.
• Cost spikes appear in certain months, notably large jumps for 'Support Multibeam' and 'Production Support' from May to November, signaling possible release, incident or project cycles driving resource allocation.
• Initiatives with very low spend (e.g., 'ROAM', 'Feature Refinement') may represent deprioritized or highly efficient activities.
Summary: The majority of cost and SDLC activity appears concentrated in post-production support and environment management, with some initiatives showing minimal allocation, suggesting a strong focus on operational reliability and infrastructure over new development.

output:
# Board Analysis: REBEL-Scrum (December 1–31, 2025)

## Executive Summary
During December 2025, **REBEL-Scrum** delivered modest throughput and velocity ahead of the mid-month holiday slowdown. Average cycle time remained steady at **6.44 days**, with total throughput of **10 items** and total velocity of **48 points** over four active weeks. Quality was stable (avg. **3.73/5**), but sprint scope creep peaked at **102%**, contributing to zero completions in the latter half of the month. Process-mining reveals high rework (28 backward transitions) and skipped steps (44), indicating refinement and Definition-of-Ready gaps.

----

## Key Metric Summary

| **Metric**                                          | **Value** |
| :---                                                | ---:      |
| **Average cycle time (days)**                       | 6.44      |
| **Total throughput (items completed)**              | 10        |
| **Total velocity (story points)**                   | 48        |
| **Average quality rating (1–5)**                    | 3.73      |
| **Average sprint scope creep (% added scope)**      | 82.37     |

----

## Weekly Trends

### Cycle Time & Throughput

| **Week starting** | **Cycle time (days)** | **Throughput (items)** |
| :---              | ---:                  | ---:                   |
| 2025-12-01        | 6.64                  | 6                      |
| 2025-12-08        | 6.24                  | 4                      |
| 2025-12-15        | 0                     | 0                      |
| 2025-12-22        | 0                     | 0                      |
| 2025-12-29        | 0                     | 0                      |

*Note: Zero values from Dec 15 onward coincide with year-end ramp-down.*

### Velocity & Quality
- **Average velocity:** 12 points/week (total **48** points over four weeks).
- **Average quality rating:** 3.73/5 (range 3.60–3.85).

----

## Sprint Scope Creep
- Began at **43.94%**, rising to **102.27%** by mid-month and remaining at that level.
- Indicates that unplanned work more than doubled planned scope, impacting delivery.

----

## Process Flow Insights

### Process Metrics

| **Metric**            | **Count** |
| :---                  | ---:      |
| **Total tasks**       | 25        |
| **Backward transitions** | 28     |
| **Skipped tasks**     | 44        |
| **Blocked tasks**     | 0         |

### Top Transition Frequencies

| **Transition**               | **Count** |
| :---                         | ---:      |
| refinement → ready           | 17        |
| ready → development          | 15        |
| development → in review      | 10        |
| testing → acceptance         | 9         |
| in review → testing          | 8         |

### Common Paths
- 8 tasks stopped after **refinement** only.
- Only 4 tasks followed the full ideal path: refinement → ready → development → in review → testing → acceptance → done.
- Multiple tasks looped between stages, highlighting rework and unclear handoffs.

----

## Interpretation & Recommendations
1. **Mitigate scope creep**  
   - Enforce stricter Definition of Ready criteria to limit unplanned additions.  
   - Expected improvement: reducing scope creep by 20% could restore mid-month throughput (~4 additional items).

2. **Balance workload around holidays**  
   - Introduce a shortened sprint plan for end-of-year to maintain at least baseline throughput.  
   - Reserve 15–20% capacity for critical tasks to avoid full ramp-down.

3. **Improve refinement and handoff clarity**  
   - Hold targeted refinement workshops; define “ready” exit criteria.  
   - Anticipated benefit: decrease backward transitions by 30%, reducing cycle time by ~1 day.

4. **Monitor process compliance**  
   - Set WIP limits on in-review and testing stages to prevent task bouncing.  
   - Aim to reduce skipped tasks by 25%, improving end-to-end flow consistency.

Implementing these steps should stabilize delivery, enhance predictability, and reduce rework for REBEL-Scrum in early 2026.

Between December 10 and December 23, progress was initially slow, with a growing amount of work in progress and limited completed tasks, causing the team's status to slip from 'On Track' to 'Off Track' and 'At Risk' for both tasks and points. Notable turnaround began on December 22, with rapid completion: by December 23, 9 out of 10 tasks were done and 22 out of 27 points completed, putting the team back 'On Track.'

Key findings:
- Mid-cycle overload: Too many tasks in progress early on, far above the ideal pace.
- Risk & Recovery: Team lingered in an 'Off Track' state until a late surge was made to complete tasks in the final days.
- Successful finish: By the end, nearly all backlog and WIP were cleared, with strong throughput but indicating possible crunch or bottleneck late in the work period.

- Several areas (ABP OBP IFE Release Management, ESA Capability Expansion, Architectural Runway) showed ramp-ups late in the year, possibly reflecting shifting priorities.
- Consistent monthly expenditure in continuous support- and maintenance-oriented work reflects ongoing business needs.
- Opportunities exist to review high-cost, multi-month initiatives for value delivery alignment and potential cost optimization.

The data shows that cycle times for 3-point issues are volatile, ranging from as low as 4.55 days to a spike of 19.66 days, indicating potential obstacles or bottlenecks with larger tasks. In contrast, 2-point and 1-point issues have generally lower and more stable cycle times, typically under 10 days, but also exhibit occasional spikes. Key insights:

- Larger (3-point) items experience the most variability and the longest delays, suggesting a review of blockers for high-complexity work may be needed.
- Cycle times for all issue sizes improved in late September/early October, then worsened by November. This may coincide with process or resource changes.
- Ensuring consistent cycle times—especially for larger work items—can improve predictability and team throughput.

• Most recent data (Dec 2025) shows 720/793 tasks completed (~91%), with forecasts indicating continued timely delivery.
• No future tasks are included in the actuals; projections show closure of outstanding work by 2026.
